BaseComment: multiplication for 6 (3 ⋅ 2), 7 (3 ⋅ 2 + 1), 8 (4 ⋅ 2); possibly subtraction for 9 in some versions; 11 to 19 = 10 + n

Name: Yakoma, CAR, DR of the Congo
Yangben (Nuasue), Cameroon
BaseComment: 6 - 9 are compounds whose constituents are not discernible

Name: Asmat (Keenakap)
BaseComment: subtraction for 4 (one finger remaining); 5 contains hand; 6 to 9 = 5 + n

Name: Dodalim
BaseComment: 4 = 2 + 2; distinct 3; or 3 = x + 2; 5 = 2 + 2 + 1; or 5 contains hand

Name: Yemba (Dschang), Cameroon
BaseComment: 6 - 9 are compounds whose constituents are not discernible

Name: Biksi
BaseComment: 3 = 2 + 1, 4 = 2 + 2 (distinct 2 ?); also binary+4 or ternary elements in some dialects (4 = 3 + 1; 5 = 3 + 2)

Name: Yopno, Papua New Guinea
BaseComment: 4 is various forms of doubling; 5 contains hand

Name: Yoruba, Nigeria, Benin
BaseComment: quinary, decimal, vigesimal, 25 = 30-1 … 28 = 30-2, 29=30-1, 30 is an atom

Name: Zanaki, Tanzania
BaseComment: 6-9 are derived from different bases. Form of 10 that serves as base for higher numerals seems borrowed. 100 and 1000 are atoms

Name: Zande, CAR, DR of the Congo
BaseComment: 15 is an atom. Borrowings in 70 and 90 and 100

Name: Zia, Papua New Guinea
BaseComment: 3 = 2 + 1; formation of 4 varies among dialects; 5 = hand one

Name: Zinza, Tanzania
BaseComment: 6-9 are derived forms but the constituents are not discernible

Name: Zulu, South Africa, Lesotho
BaseComment: 6-9 are derived forms but the constituents are not discernible
